#. type: Content of: <guide><title>
#: en/articles/lvm-p2.xml:6
#, no-wrap
msgid "Learning Linux LVM, Part 2"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><abstract>
#: en/articles/lvm-p2.xml:14
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In this article, Daniel shares his experiences converting cvs.gentoo.org's\n"
"/home filesystem to an LVM logical volume. After the transition, we get to see\n"
"the benefits of LVM when cvs.gentoo.org's /home partition is dynamically\n"
"resized in real-time, without rebooting, unmounting /home, or even dropping to\n"
"runlevel 1. All processes continue to work without any interruption. Daniel's\n"
"step-by-step details of the conversion will help anyone interested in peforming\n"
"a similar transition on their own machine.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><title>
#: en/articles/lvm-p2.xml:32
#, no-wrap
msgid "The cvs.gentoo.org upgrade"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lvm-p2.xml:34
#, no-wrap
msgid "Introduction"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lvm-p2.xml:38
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In <uri link=\"/doc/en/articles/lvm-p1.xml\">my first LVM article</uri>, I\n"
"explained the concepts behind LVM. Now it's time to put LVM into action. In\n"
"this article, I'm going to set up LVM on the official Gentoo Linux cvs server,\n"
"cvs.gentoo.org. Although cvs.gentoo.org has only one hard drive, LVM's\n"
"flexibility still provides an incredible improvement over the standard static\n"
"partitioning approach. I'll show you all the steps of the LVM conversion\n"
"process, so that if you're interested you can perform a similar conversion on\n"
"one of your machines.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><warn>
#: en/articles/lvm-p2.xml:49
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Because implementing LVM is a major change to the system (involving the\n"
"creation of new partitions and other potentially hazardous actions) it's a\n"
"really good idea to perform a full system backup before beginning this process.\n"
"If you're not going to perform a backup, I hope you're using a test box with no\n"
"important data on it. I should mention that I didn't experience any problems\n"
"while converting to LVM, but it's best to be prepared in case something goes\n"
"wrong.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lvm-p2.xml:59
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"That said, let's continue. Before starting the conversion process, I upgraded\n"
"cvs.gentoo.org so that it was using the following packages. At the time I\n"
"performed the LVM transition, these were the latest versions available (see\n"
"<uri link=\"#resources\">Resources</uri> later in this article):\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/articles/lvm-p2.xml:66
#, no-wrap
msgid "Linux kernel 2.4.1-ac19"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/articles/lvm-p2.xml:67
#, no-wrap
msgid "LVM 0.9.1_beta5"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/articles/lvm-p2.xml:68
#, no-wrap
msgid "reiserfs-utils 3.6.25"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lvm-p2.xml:72
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now, for the hard drive. cvs.gentoo.org had a nice new IBM 45 GB hard drive\n"
"sitting in it; however, when I installed Gentoo Linux on cvs, I only\n"
"partitioned about 10 gigabytes of the drive, keeping the remaining 35 GB for\n"
"future partitions. Such are the little tricks you need to employ when not using\n"
"LVM -- leaving part of the drive unpartitioned is a primitive but effective way\n"
"to allow for future expansion. However, with LVM there is a better approach.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lvm-p2.xml:83
#, no-wrap
msgid "The space problem"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lvm-p2.xml:87
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In the past few weeks, I had been noticing that my root ReiserFS partition had\n"
"been slowly filling up, as you can see from this <c>df</c> output:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lvm-p2.xml:91
#, no-wrap
msgid "Shrinking free space"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lvm-p2.xml:92
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Filesystem           1k-blocks      Used Available Use% Mounted on\n"
"/dev/hda3              9765200   6989312   2775888  72% /\n"
"tmpfs                   269052         0    269052   0% /dev/shm\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lvm-p2.xml:98
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now, a 72% full root partition isn't exactly a crisis, but it isn't a wonderful\n"
"situation either. ReiserFS, like many other filesystems, starts slowing down as\n"
"it gets more and more full, and it was just a matter of time before my root\n"
"filesystem would fill up completely and filesystem performance would take a\n"
"hit.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lvm-p2.xml:106
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"I decided to fix this problem by using LVM to create a new logical volume out\n"
"of the 35 GB of currently unpartitioned space at the end of my hard drive.\n"
"Then, I'd create a filesystem on this volume and move a good chunk of the\n"
"contents of <path>/dev/hda3</path> to it.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lvm-p2.xml:113
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you're thinking of making a similar transition on one of your machines, the\n"
"first thing you need to do is find a suitable piece of your root filesystem to\n"
"move to a logical volume. For me, the choice was easy -- my <path>/home</path>\n"
"tree was taking up around 5.7 GB. By moving <path>/home</path> to its own LVM\n"
"logical volume, my root filesystem would then be at about 20% capacity. Since\n"
"most new data is being added to <path>/home</path>, my root filesystem would\n"
"likely stay at around 20% capacity as well -- a very healthy situation.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lvm-p2.xml:125
#, no-wrap
msgid "The beginnings of a solution"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lvm-p2.xml:129
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To begin the conversion, I first had to partition the unused space at the end\n"
"of my hard drive. Using <c>cfdisk</c>, I created a 35 GB partition\n"
"(<path>/dev/hda5</path>) and set the partition type of the partition to\n"
"<c>8E</c> (the official LVM partition type). After this change, I rebooted to\n"
"force a reread of my partition table. After the reboot, my partition table\n"
"looked like this:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lvm-p2.xml:137
#, no-wrap
msgid "The new partition table"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lvm-p2.xml:138
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# <i>sfdisk -l</i>\n"
"Disk /dev/hda: 89355 cylinders, 16 heads, 63 sectors/track\n"
"Units = cylinders of 516096 bytes, blocks of 1024 bytes, counting from 0\n"
"   Device Boot Start     End   #cyls   #blocks   Id  System\n"
"/dev/hda1   *      0+    247     248-   124960+  83  Linux\n"
"/dev/hda2        248     743     496    249984   82  Linux swap\n"
"/dev/hda3        744   20119   19376   9765504   83  Linux\n"
"/dev/hda4      20120   89354   69235  34894440    5  Extended\n"
"/dev/hda5      20120+  89354   69235- 34894408+  8e  Linux LVM\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lvm-p2.xml:150
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now that I had an empty 35 GB partition, I was ready to initialize it for LVM.\n"
"Here's the procedure -- first, I would initialize the 35 gigabytes as a\n"
"<e>physical</e> volume; then, I would create a <e>volume</e> group using this\n"
"physical volume, and finally, I would allocate some of the extents on the\n"
"volume group, creating a <e>logical volume</e> that would contain my new\n"
"filesystem and house all the files currently in <path>/home</path>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lvm-p2.xml:159
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To begin the process, I used the <c>pvcreate</c> command to initialize\n"
"<path>/dev/hda5</path> as a physical volume:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lvm-p2.xml:163
#, no-wrap
msgid "Creating the physical volume"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lvm-p2.xml:164
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# <i>pvcreate /dev/hda5</i>\n"
"pvcreate -- physical volume \"/dev/hda5\" successfully created\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lvm-p2.xml:169
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<c>pvcreate</c> set up a special \"accounting\" area on <path>/dev/hda5</path>,\n"
"called the VGDA (volume group descriptor area). LVM uses this area to keep\n"
"track of how the physical extents are allocated, among other things.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lvm-p2.xml:175
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"My next step was to create a volume group and add <path>/dev/hda5</path> to\n"
"this group. The volume group would act as a pool of extents (chunks of storage\n"
"blocks). Once the volume group was created, I could create as many logical\n"
"volumes as I wanted. I decided that my volume group would be called \"main\":\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lvm-p2.xml:181
#, no-wrap
msgid "Creating the volume group"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lvm-p2.xml:182
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# <i>vgcreate main /dev/hda5</i>\n"
"vgcreate -- INFO: using default physical extent size 4 MB\n"
"vgcreate -- INFO: maximum logical volume size is 255.99 Gigabyte\n"
"vgcreate -- doing automatic backup of volume group \"main\"\n"
"vgcreate -- volume group \"main\" successfully created and activated\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lvm-p2.xml:190
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The <c>vgcreate</c> command did a couple of things. In addition to creating the\n"
"\"main\" volume group, it also set up <path>/dev/hda5</path> to use 4 MB extents,\n"
"the default extent size. This means that any logical volumes I create from this\n"
"volume group can be expanded and shrunk in 4 MB increments.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lvm-p2.xml:197
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Due to kernel limitations, the extent size determines the maximum size that a\n"
"logical volume can be. As you can see from the above output, a 4 MB extent size\n"
"imposes a logical volume size limitation of 256 gigabytes, which is an easily\n"
"attainable logical volume size if you're adding several high-capacity drives to\n"
"your volume group. If your volumes could end up being greater than 256 GB\n"
"apiece, I recommend specifying a larger extent size at <c>vgcreate</c> time.\n"
"Extents can range anywhere from 8 KB to 512 MB, and must always be a multiple\n"
"of two. By increasing the extent size above 4 MB, the maximum physical volume\n"
"size will be scaled accordingly, up to a maximum of 1 petabyte (although the\n"
"current real-world size limit is 2 terabytes on x86 systems). For example, if I\n"
"wanted to create a volume group with 32 megabyte extents, I'd type:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lvm-p2.xml:210
#, no-wrap
msgid "A larger extent size"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lvm-p2.xml:211
#, no-wrap
msgid "# <i>vgcreate -s 32M main /dev/hda5</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lvm-p2.xml:215
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"32 MB is a good extent size, since a 32 MB granularity is still manageable and\n"
"pushes the maximum logical volume size to 2 terabytes to boot. Once your volume\n"
"group is created, you can view its information by typing <c>vgdisplay</c>:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lvm-p2.xml:220
#, no-wrap
msgid "Examining volume information"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lvm-p2.xml:221
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# <i>vgdisplay</i>\n"
"--- Volume group ---\n"
"VG Name               main\n"
"VG Access             read/write\n"
"VG Status             available/resizable\n"
"VG #                  0\n"
"MAX LV                256\n"
"Cur LV                0\n"
"Open LV               0\n"
